headline: Intuit Stock Falls on Weaker Guidance, but CEO Downplays Fears of Free U.S. Tax App
summary: Intuit Chief Executive Sasan Goodarzi doesn’t expect president-elect Donald Trump’s incoming administration to build a free tax-filing app that would interfere with its business.  Intuit reiterated its full-year guidance as it reported fiscal first-quarter earnings Thursday, but shares fell 5% after hours when the company guided for a weaker-than-expected second quarter.  Shares for the tax-preparation software maker fell this week, along with those of competitor H&R Block, after The Washington Post reported that leaders overseeing the Department of Government Efficiency discussed creating a mobile app for Americans to file their taxes for free with the Internal Revenue Service.

headline: Ross Stores, Intuit shares post big moves on earnings
summary: Ross Stores (ROST) and Intuit (INTU) both reported quarterly results after the closing bell, and posted big moves in opposite directions. Ross reported mixed results for the third quarter, with profit beating estimates but revenue missed. The company blamed hurricanes and unseasonably warm weather for the miss on sales. But it was the company's guidance that drove shares higher after hours. Ross Stores raised its full year EPS guidance, now seeing a profit of $6.10 to $6.17 per share, up from $6.00 to $6.13. On the flipside, shares of Intuit were under pressure, and guidance is the issue. Fiscal first quarter results topped analyst expectations, but the company's outlook for the second quarter is raising investor concerns. The software giant sees adjusted earnings per share of $2.55 to $2.61 versus the estimate of $3.23. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination Overtime here. This post was written by Rachel Sherman.

headline: Intuit's quarterly forecasts disappoint as delayed promotions weigh on growth
summary: Intuit's consumer group, which caters to individuals, is expected to see a single-digit revenue decline in the second quarter due to the delay in promotions for the desktop offering of TurboTax, its software widely used by Americans to file their taxes. The company said the delay only impacts the current quarter and reiterated its annual forecast for double-digit revenue growth. Intuit offers financial products, including personal finance portal Credit Karma, marketing platform Mailchimp and accounting software suite QuickBooks that help small businesses manage their finances.
